  "statement": "# Merge Triplets to Form Target Triplet\n\nReturn whether selected triplets can be coordinate-wise merged to exactly equal `target`.\n\n## Examples\n\n**Example 1**\n\n```text\nInput: triplets = [[2,5,3],[1,8,4],[1,7,5]], target = [2,7,5]\nOutput: true\n```\n\n**Example 2**\n\n```text\nInput: triplets = [[3,4,5],[4,5,6]], target = [3,2,5]\nOutput: false\n```\n\n**Example 3**\n\n```text\nInput: triplets = [[1,1,1]], target = [1,1,1]\nOutput: true\n```\n\n## Constraints\n\n- Inputs are sized for local offline execution.\n- Return the value described by the method signature.",
  "editorial": "Track the local choice that leaves the most room for future choices, or sort intervals so conflicts can be resolved with one pass.",
  "solution_notes": "```python\nclass Solution:\n    def mergeTriplets(self, triplets, target):\n        good = [False, False, False]\n        for triplet in triplets:\n            if all(triplet[i] <= target[i] for i in range(3)):\n                for i in range(3): good[i] |= triplet[i] == target[i]\n        return all(good)\n```",
  "hints": [
    "Sort first when relative order drives the decision.",
    "Keep the smallest state that proves future feasibility."
  ],
  "starter_code": {
    "python": "class Solution:\n    def mergeTriplets(self, triplets, target):\n        pass\n"
  },
